\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Physical and environmental controls prevent unauthorized physical access,
 environmental damage,
 and interruption of operations for County information systems and the Criminal Justice Information (CJI) they process.
 This policy defines the requirements governing perimeter,
 monitoring,
 environmental,
 and power infrastructure safeguards required to satisfy the physical security mandates of the FBI CJIS Security Policy,
 and establishes the routing by which physical security findings enter the incident response and compliance monitoring processes of the Information Operations Policy Manual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Physically Secure Locations and Perimeter Controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure the perimeter of any physically secure location housing critical information technology infrastructure or processing Criminal Justice Information (CJI) is structurally separated from non-secure locations by physical controls (locked doors,
 card readers,
 or equivalent) and is clearly signed at entry points to designate restricted access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall position information system devices to prevent unauthorized individuals from accessing or visually observing Criminal Justice Information (CJI) or sensitive administrative sessions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Access Control Procedures
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall maintain physical access audit logs for all physically secure information technology locations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall ensure physical access audit logs record all access events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall retain physical access audit logs in accordance with Nevada LRDA 20071749 (Property Management:
 Security Records).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All County Personnel issued physical access credentials shall not leave keys,
 key fobs,
 access cards,
 or combination codes unattended in locations accessible to unauthorized individuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All County Personnel issued physical access credentials shall not share keys,
 key fobs,
 access cards,
 or combination codes among personnel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall direct that combinations and keys are changed,
 and access cards deactivated and reissued,
 whenever:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(a) a key is lost or a combination is believed to have been compromised.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(b) an individual possessing a key,
 combination,
 or unescorted access credential is transferred to a role not requiring access or is separated from the County.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Physical Access Authorizations and Visitor Control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall approve the access list of individuals authorized to enter physically secure information technology locations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall maintain the access list in the System of Engagement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall review and update the access list no less than annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall execute physical access credential issuance,
 modification,
 and revocation for all secure information technology facilities in accordance with the personnel onboarding and offboarding framework established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Upon notification of personnel separation or role change,
 System and Network Administrators shall revoke physical access credentials (keycards,
 key fobs,
 and combination codes) on the Involuntary Termination and Standard Termination timelines established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall maintain a visitor control log recording the names,
 organizations,
 dates,
 entry and exit times,
 and forms of identification used to authenticate every visitor accessing a physically secure location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All County Personnel shall escort visitors at all times within secure areas.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Constraint
\series default
:
 When the escort involves vendor or contractor personnel performing maintenance on systems that process,
 store,
 or transmit Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 the Information Operations Department shall designate an escort who meets the personnel security clearance requirements for Criminal Justice Information (CJI) access established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and who is technically qualified to supervise the specific maintenance activity being performed.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall conduct a review of visitor access records no less than quarterly to assess whether access authorizations remain current for County operational needs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall report anomalies identified during visitor access record reviews — including unauthorized access patterns,
 missing records,
 or entries outside authorized access periods — to the IT Director,
 and,
 for anomalies involving facilities processing Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 to the IT Director (as LASO) for CJIS Systems Agency notification assessment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Retention Mandate
\series default
:
 System and Network Administrators shall retain the visitor control log for a minimum period of three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year to which the log pertains,
 in accordance with Nevada LRDA 20071749 (Property Management:
 Security Records).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Monitoring Physical Access and Camera Surveillance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure physical access to facilities where information systems reside is monitored to detect and respond to physical security incidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Motion Detection Configuration
\series default
:
 System and Network Administrators shall configure security cameras in server rooms and network closets with motion detection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Alert Routing
\series default
:
 System and Network Administrators shall configure the monitoring system to notify the Information Operations Department via email on motion detection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Out-of-Hours Follow-Up
\series default
:
 System and Network Administrators shall configure the monitoring system to generate a work order on any motion event occurring outside Information Operations Department hours of operation,
 to be actioned by end of the next business day.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Rationale
\series default
:
 Camera-based motion alerting satisfies the physical intrusion alarm requirement under CJIS Security Policy v6.0 Section PE-6(1).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall review physical access logs no less than quarterly,
 and following any physical,
 environmental,
 or security-related incident involving Criminal Justice Information (CJI) or systems used to process,
 store,
 or transmit CJI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall coordinate the results of physical access log reviews and any physical security investigations with the County's incident response capability in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Retention Mandate
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall retain security camera recordings that monitor physical access for a minimum of seven (7) calendar days or for the period needed to review the recordings,
 whichever is longer,
 in accordance with Nevada LRDA 20200003 (Property Management:
 Security Camera Recordings).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall determine any extension beyond seven (7) calendar days required to complete review.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
When camera footage captures an incident,
 breach,
 or legal event,
 the Assistant IT Director shall export the relevant segment of footage within twenty-four (24) hours of discovery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall report the event in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall reclassify the exported footage segment as an incident record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall retain the reclassified incident record in accordance with the evidence artifact retention framework established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Environmental Controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fire Protection
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure facilities containing critical information technology infrastructure employ automatic fire suppression and fire detection systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure fire suppression and fire detection systems are inspected no less than annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall configure fire detection systems to activate automatically upon detection of fire conditions and to simultaneously notify organizational incident response personnel and local emergency responders without requiring manual intervention.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Temperature and Humidity Controls
\series default
:
 Buildings and Grounds shall maintain automated temperature and humidity controls for primary server rooms to prevent environmental degradation of information systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Water Damage Protection
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure master shutoff valves are identified and accessible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall position or elevate information technology equipment to minimize risk from water damage.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Power Equipment,
 Emergency Infrastructure,
 and Continuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Power Equipment and Cabling
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall protect power equipment and power cabling serving critical information technology infrastructure from physical damage and destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure cabling paths are identified,
 documented,
 and physically secured within locked conduits or restricted-access routing pathways.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Shutoff
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure facilities housing critical information technology infrastructure provide the capability to shut off power to all information systems in emergency situations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall place emergency shutoff switches or devices in locations readily accessible to authorized personnel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall protect emergency shutoff capability from unauthorized or accidental activation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Power
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall ensure critical information technology facilities are equipped with an uninterruptible power supply (UPS) providing near-instantaneous protection from power interruptions and facilitating orderly system shutdown or transition to an alternate power source upon loss of primary power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System and Network Administrators shall maintain UPS units in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 lifecycle standards.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Lighting
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall maintain automatic emergency lighting that activates upon power outage or disruption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Buildings and Grounds shall ensure emergency lighting covers emergency exits and evacuation routes within the facility.
\end_layout

\end_deeper

